04857nam a22006615i 9780226373553DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263735537 a10.7208/97802263735532doi  a(DE-B1597)525043  a(OCoLC)954533878  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHQ154.S26bR58 2017 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.740972862231 aRivers-Moore, Megan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGringo Gulch :bSex, Tourism, and Social Mobility in Costa Rica /cMegan Rivers-Moore. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b10 halftones, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Commerce of Sex in Costa Rica -- t2. Almighty Gringos and the Relational Economy of Sex Tourism -- t3. Selling Sex, Selling Care: Aff ective Labor in the Tourism Sector -- t4. Motherhood, Consumption, and the Purchase of Respectability -- t5. The State and the Sex Industry -- t6. Good for the State, Bad for the Nation: Race, Space, and Migration -- tConclusion: Getting Ahead in Gringo Gulch -- tMethodological Appendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe story of sex tourism in the Gringo Gulch neighborhood of San José, Costa Rica could be easily cast as the exploitation of poor local women by privileged North American men-men who are in a position to take advantage of the vast geopolitical inequalities that make Latin American women into suppliers of low-cost sexual labor. But in Gringo Gulch, Megan Rivers-Moore tells a more nuanced story, demonstrating that all the actors intimately entangled in the sex tourism industry-sex workers, sex tourists, and the state-use it as a strategy for getting ahead. Rivers-Moore situates her ethnography at the intersections of gender, race, class, and national dimensions in the sex industry. Instead of casting sex workers as hapless victims and sex tourists as neoimperialist racists, she reveals each group as involved in a complicated process of class mobility that must be situated within the sale and purchase of leisure and sex. These interactions operate within an almost entirely unregulated but highly competitive market beyond the reach of the state-bringing a distinctly neoliberal cast to the market. Throughout the book, Rivers-Moore introduces us to remarkable characters-Susan, a mother of two who doesn't regret her career of sex work; Barry, a teacher and father of two from Virginia who travels to Costa Rica to escape his loveless, sexless marriage; Nancy, a legal assistant in the Department of Labor who is shocked to find out that prostitution is legal and still unregulated. Gringo Gulch is a fascinating and groundbreaking look at sex tourism, Latin America, and the neoliberal state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aNeoliberalismxSocial aspectszCosta RicazSan José. 0aProstituteszCosta RicazSan JoséxSocial conditions. 0aProstitutionzCosta RicazSan José. 0aSex tourismzCosta RicazSan José. 4aCosta Rica. 4aLatin America. 4aethnography. 4aneoliberalism. 4asex work. 4asocial mobility. 4atourism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226373553423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226373553.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  Univers